@NODE AD Introduction

 Remember that ancient DirOpus, which let you double-click on a font if  you
 wanted  to view it? Well, ever since I got me a new (legal) version of Dir-
 Opus (version 5.11) this feature didn't work anymore.  Since  this  annoyed
 me,  I  started  to  look  on  the  AmiNet for a program to view fonts in a
 similar manner. As I found one, it happened to be a SHAREWARE program,  and
 also  it  didn't interact with DirOpus. As I don't believe in shareware for
 those tiny little programs, I immediately discarded it  from  my  harddrive
 and decided to write my own.

 Along the road of development, I decided that it would be nice if this pro-
 gram  could also be used without DirOpus. After a couple of days I finished
 programming, and thus Shelley V1.00 was born. :-)

 As I find it hard to determine how a font looks in reality if only the cha-
 racter set is shown, Shelley displays the text of 'My Way' but is also able
 to show the complete character  set of the  font. It's up to you  to make a
 choice.

 As I mentioned before, I don't believe in shareware for those  tiny  little
 programs on  which  the  author spend just a couple of hours. So Shelley is
 FREEWARE. You may do with it whatever your want,  regarding  the  copyright
 notes.

@ENDNODE


@NODE AE Features

 · Small and fast

 · Low memory usage: uses SimpleRefresh window

 · Displays the song text of 'My Way' or the character set

 · Easy to use

@ENDNODE


@NODE AF "System Requirements"

 · OS 3.0+.

 · reqtools.library V38+

@ENDNODE


@NODE AG Installation

 Just copy it anywhere you want.

@ENDNODE


@NODE AH Usage

 Shelley knows two modes: Workbench mode and CLI mode. In CLI mode, there is
 no way to load another font. This is no programming error, but intentional-
 ly done so. You are in CLI mode when you run  Showfont  from  CLI  with  an
 argument. Running Shelley from CLI with no argument acts as Workbench mode.

 If you double-click on the icon, a file requester will pop up  to  let  you
 choose  a  font. Just double-click on the font size of your choice. You are
 now in Workbench mode. You may use the RMB to re-open the file requester to
 select  another  font.  Pressing  HELP opens the built-in Help window which
 explains how to control Shelley. I am not going to explain all that here.

 In CLI mode no requester  will pop up, but the font  is immediately  shown.
 You  have to specify both the font name (eventually with full path) and the
 font size, separated by a slash ( '/' ). As in Workbench mode pressing  the
 RMB  will  re-open  the file requester, this acts slightly different in CLI
 mode. Pressing the RMB will quit Shelley.

 In CLI mode when you want to view a font in the FONTS:  drawer,  you  don't
 have  to specify the path (e.g. Courier/15 will do) but if you want to view
 a font outside the FONTS: drawer you have to specify the  full  path  (e.g.
 MyDisk:FontDrawer/MyFont/13).


 Keep in mind that  Shelley does  not show ROM fonts but only disk fonts. So
 if you manage to select  e.g. Topaz/8 (???), or type it in a CLI window, it
 won't be displayed. The closest disk font will be displayed instead.  Also,
 Shelley only displays designed fonts. This means that a font which you want
 to view, actually must reside on a disk. For example,  typing  at  the  CLI
 prompt: 'Shelley  Courier/40'  when Courier 40 is not in the FONTS: drawer,
 will cause Shelley to display the closest size.

 Also keep in mind that the Info window does not accept any input at all!

@ENDNODE


